{"/service/ndnp/sdhi/batch_sdhi_carrot_ver02/data/sn96090217/00279522928/1921020401/1114.xml":{"full_text":"\u25a0!V\n\u00dcBSCRJPTION,\nPeople who make the most noise\ngenerally have tlie least to say.\nGood advice is seldom acceptable be\ncause its quality is not recognized.\nLenin, the Russian dictator, denies\nthat lie is dead. Possibly he knows.\nRegardless of price conditions, the\ncrop of free advice has not diminished\nHurrah for the fellow who says\nhurrah forthls town! Are you guilt} V\nThere\u2019s a master mind in eve r y\nhome, but sometimes it isn't spelled\nthat way.\nIt\u2019s no trouble at all to speak a kind\nword. Just think it and it will slip\nright out.\nYou can always tell when a fellow\nhas reached his dotage. He calls her\nhis \u201cwonder girl.\u201d\nWe, thank you, are perfectly satis\nfied with lU2L. Each day is quite as\nwe expected it to be.\nSenator Thomas is quite correct:\nthe bootlegging.lftdustry probably is\nour most flourishing industry.\nCharity invariably begins at home,\nbut in most cases there is not enough\nto go beyond the first person.\nYes, William, spring is ambling\nright along. But it has no originality\n\u2014it does the same each year.\nMr. Harding approaches the 4th of\nMarch in fear and.trembling. He may\nforget the first line of his speech.\nWise men of the world would soon\nbecome bored if it were not for the\nfools who afford them amusement.\nParis has decided to tax homes em\nploying domestic servants. That\nought to tax the family\u2019s patience.\nThis is a prodigal world, after all.\nMen pay 50 cents for a hair cut and\nthen go right out and let it grow a\ngain.\nDon\u2019t force too much goodness onto\nthe boy while he is young. Leave a\nlittle for his old age, and he won\u2019t\nforget.\nJapanese lioerals are said to be in\ntensely desirous of friendship with\nAmerica. There are at least a dozen\nof them.\nThe South Dakota referendum ma\nchinery is not likely to become rusty\nas long as Dick Richards\u2019 mind re\nmains active.\nSome men draw lemons in the gar*\nden of iove but even they are an im\nprovement over the persimmons the\nwomen occasionally get.\nBroad shoulders and narrow hips\nwill be the style for men this spring.\nBut that won't bother us\u2014we never\ndid care for style anvway.\n\u201cIt requires a thick skinned man\nto hold public office these days,\" re\nmarks a leading citizen. But he is in\nerror. All hide would be better.\n0 f\nSermons flashed by wireless tele\nphone so people can stay home and\nhear them are being tried out in the\neast. How about the collection?\nEmma Goldman says she is mighty\naick of soviet Rvssla, and wants to re\nturn to America. But at that she\ncan hardly realize how we felt toward\nher.\nCourtesy requires that you laugh\nheartily when your friend tells a joke\nIf you start at the wrong time he'll\nmerely think he has improved upon\nthe telling.\nSome men have the habit of making\npert remarks about women and girls\nthey see on the street\u2014but they are\nnever their own mothers, wives or sta\nte** It makes a difference you know\nTh e Attorney General of South Da\nkota haa given notice that if the pre\n-1 sent legislature does not enact an en\nforceable Sunday observance law, he\nwill proceed to enforce the Sunday\n1 \u201cblue laws\" already on the statute\nbooks and see how the people like it.\nfy V'\"'\nBSrnS\nt 1\nm\n4 f 'j l\nti\nTHE MELLETTE COUNTY PIONEER\nPublished By FRED C. KIRCH\nEntered as second class mall matter at\nWood. S. March 23. 1912. under act of\nMarch 3.1879.\nForeign Advertifin\u00bbr Representative\n|_ THEAMERK AN I I 5S< lA] ION\n\u201cOne Country-One Flag\"\nThe love that never grows less isn't\nlove\u2014it\u2019s greed.\nSoon, now, the grass will begin to\ngrow again, but don't let it be under\nyour feet.\nR. Richards of Huron, has pre\npared and had introduced in the low\ner house of the South Dakota legisla\nture a bill standardizing citizenship\nto individual responsibility under the\n\u201clegal merit system\u201d to stimulate\nmorality as a basis for temperance.\nThe measure is the embodiment of a\nplatform on which Mr. Richards\nsought the governorship last fall.\nUnder the terms oi the bill, the sal\noons oj public drinking places would\nbe prohibited but licensed pharmacists\nand druggists and wholesale and re\ntail grocers who are \"moral citizens\u201d\nmay sell \u201cstimulants\u201d after procuring\nmunicipal moral permits. A record\nof \u201cmoral citizenship\u201d of all persons\nin the state will be kept and persons\nconvicted by a jury of\u2018being imoral\nwould be placed on the \u201cblacklist.\u201d\nThey would lose the right to vote at\nany town, county, state or national\nelection and would bl unable to buy\n\u201cstimulonts\u201d legally. The introduc\ntion of this bill proved to be a sort of\na bombshell among the member 4 of\nthe house, and it took them unawares\nThe bill will hardly be adopted by\nthis legislature, but Dick Richards is\na persevering sort of acus, and if his\nbill meets with defeat at the hands\nof the present legislature, no doubt\nhe wfll take it to the people, and they\nwill have a chance to vote on it at the\nnext general election, and it will also\nprove to be a good excuse for Dick to\ncontinue in the political lime light iu\nthis state, and the taxpayers will foot\nthe bill of his eccentrecies. If the\nmeasure should finally be .adopted by\nthe people of this state we are at a\nloss to know what will become of the\nfederal prohibition act.\n$2.00\nPROSPERITY AHEAD\nThere is much comfort to be had\nfrom the statement recently of Judge\nElbert H. Gary, head of the United\nStates Steel corporation, the greatest\nbusiness concern the world has ever\nproduced.\nJudge Gary says a long period of\nwonderful prosperity is just ahead of\nthe people of the United States.\nWhen Judge Gary opens ids mouth\nlie is in the habit of saying something\nand tie never says a thing uhless tie\nknows What lie is talking about.\nHe lias been a wise prophet in the\npast, because he posesses the ability\nto read conditions and possibilities as\nthey are.\nThere is no reason why tills pro\nphecy should not be one of wisdom in\nthis case, because there is no reason\nwhy we should not prosper and every\nreason why we should.\nHanks and financiers generally state\nthat we liave passed through our\nworst period of depression and are\nnow on the upgrade. Only the rank\nest kind of pessimism can hold us\nback.\nAnd who wants to be a pessimist\nwhen every human instinct spurs us\non to optimism?\nLet\u2019s demonstrate our faith in tlie\nreturn of prosperity by recognizing\nthe fact that it is here and by doing\nour share toward its maintenance in\nthis community.\nLet the watchword be production,\nwisdom in spending, and the employ\nment of a systematic course of saving.\nA proportionate amount of the pros\nperitv of the country belongs to the\npeople of this community.\nLet\u2019s get all we can and keep all we\nget.\nOther communities will be doing\nthe same.\nSCHOOL NOTES.\nINTERMEDIATE ROOM\nCarl informed us today that the peo\npie of Switzerland speak \u201cSwitch.\"\nThe Fiftli and Sixth Grades have\nbeen very busy writing stories of the\nlives of Lincoln and Washington for\ntheir booklets.\nTheodore was absent last week.\nWe hate to see a mark for absence, as\nlast month was almost a perfect\nmonth in attendance.\nOur visitors record is blank. We\nextend an invitation to all patrons, &m\nwe want you to come and see the pro\ngress your boys and girls are making.\nFrom Cambridge, Mass., comes the\nexplanation that the recent earth\nquakes throughout the world are only\ngrowing pains of newer geologic for\nmations. We\u2019d thought, at the wild\npace she\u2019s been going, Mother Earth\nwas trying to shimmy.\nMore than one half of one per cent\nof the men engaged in prohibition en\nforcement have been killed in perfor\nmance of their duty, says Wayne B.\nWheeler, anti-saloon league counsel.\nThought the Volstead act made one\nhalf of one per cent the legal limit.\nThe cry of a baby in the gallery of\nthe South Dakota bouse gallery spur\nred legislators to pass a bill permit\nting fraternal societies to Insure chil\ndren from 2 years up at a moment\nwhen opposition seemed about to de\nfeat the measure. \u201cAnd a little ahlld\nshall lead them.\"\nMOTICE TO AUTO OWNERS\nAll automobile and truok owners\nare hereby notified that they muat\nprocure their their new 1021 license\ntags without delay, or they will be\nsubject to prosecution under the law.\nGet your IW2I license tags now.\nChbis Bum*,\n62 Sheriff of Mellette county\nEl\na w| i f 1 1 r m, f\nyjt.\n\u2019aaiJ,Z\nit''i \u25a0\u2019fKr\ntHE MELLETTE COUNTY PIONEER\nBUTTE VALLEY ITEMS.\nMrs. Norup was a Wood caller Tucs\nday.\nJalia Tuell spent Sunday with Beu\nlah Krieger.\nMrs. Isaac Kaufman called on Mrs.\nNorup, Wednesday.\nMr. and Mrs. Sinclair were Wood\ncallers, Friday afternoon.\nLuther and Orlo Schaffer spent Sun\nday with Milton (Jordes.\nMrs. Ray Rankin spent Tuesday af\nternoon with Mrs. A. J. Krieger.\nJames Orr and family attended the\n\u201cDeacon Dubbs\u201d play in Wood, Sat\nurday night.\nIsaac Kaufman had the misfortune\nto lose one of his best milk cows a\nfew days ago.\nMerrill Kaufman and wife are stav\ning with Mrs. A. J. Krieger while Mr\nKrieger is away at the hospital.\nMr. and Mrs. J. L. Scull and family\nand Mr. and Mrs. Sinclair were Sun\nday afternoon callers at the Rankin\nhome.\nA. J. Krieger who met with a bad\naccident falling from a load of hay\nlast week, was taken to Winner Fri\nday night and put on the train Satur\nday morning to be taken to Rochester\nMinnesota.\nCODY CHOP STICKS\nT im P&leck went to Wldte River.\nFriday.\nMerl Simpkins went to White Riv\ner, Friday.\nJ. J. Steiner and Chas Kimball went\nto Murdo, Wednesday.\nSopha and Henry Fillbrant were\nWhile River callers, Friday.\nA few from this part of the county\nwent to the pig show and bought\nsome hog 9.\nJ. A. Bailey and two sons went to\nWhite River, Friday, and he bought a\nsow for the boys.\nSunday school at the Cody school\nhpuse beginning Jannuary 30th at\n10:30 o\u2019clock a. m.\nThe Cody Township Hoard met last\nFriday to straighten out some road\nwork that lias been done.\nSiguard Gunner has made a start in\npure bred Ilampshires by buying a\ngood sow at the Rosebud Farms, Fri\nday.\nSmall pox is thick at Wiilte River.\nYou could see people at the pig show\nwith scabs all over their faces that\nwere not well yet.\nW. J. Egleston went with Rev. Sa\nlter to the Mission, Sunday evening\nand lead the singing, there is a work\nwe all can do for the Master. Are\nyou doing yours.\nMeeting closed at the Cody school\nhouse last Saturday evening. There\nwere a few that saw the need of sal\nvation and came forward and are try\ning to walk in the light and gain eter\nnai life.\nWill Smith went to Wood Saturday\nwitli J. J. Steiner and Chas Kimball.\nIt is good to see Mr. Kimball out a\ngain, he had a hard fight with tlie\nsmall pox. The rest of the family are\nall over it now and are able to be out,\nbut they did have it hard.\nW J. Egleston bought a pure bred\nsow and a pure bred boar of the Rose\nbud Farms last Friday. These are of\nthe Hampshire breed. Also if you\nwant to go in the Hampshire* a little\nlater, just call on the Cody people and\nyou can get something good.\nPUBLIC SALE MARCH 4th,\nBeing compelled to quit business\nindefinitely on account of a cyclone\non November 2, 1920, I will sell at\nPublic Auction at our place in Wash\nington, D. C.\nOn March 4th, 1921\nThe following property to-wit:\nOne Old Democratic Platforn, which\nis in fair condition with the exception\nof several warped and worn out planks\nOne deformed League of Nations,\nsired by \u201cWoody\" and damned by\ncolleagues, can be put in working or\nder x after the spavin is removed from\nthe leagues.\nOne Democrat Donkey known as\n\u201cJimmie\" Cox, an animal without\npride of ancestry or hope of posterity.\nOne blower attachment to the U.S.\nSenate known as Scott Ferris, needs\nan extra fan.\nOne nearly new Democratic machine\n\u2022lightly out of order.\nOne old \u201cChamp\u201d Clark mower\nmade in Missouri, badly worn, may\ndo for preoinct work.\nHundreds of odds and ends that\nhave been used by me in the County\nSeats all oyer the United States, will\nbe disposed of in lots of one to ten.\nAny of the above will make some\nloyal Democrat a good souvenir.\nFree luneh served, consisting of var\nlous substitutes to be Inspected and\nlimited oy Herbert Hoover. Home\nbrew on draught.\nTerms of Sale: Your Own Time, as\nthe above assets are absolutely worth\nless to me in public life.\nColonel L. M. House\nTrustee for Wilson Affoirs\nCol. Tomolty, Auctioneer.\nWn. 0. MoAdue, Clerk. \u2014Exchange\nFllitL PROOF NOTICES.\nFinal Proof NoUcespubllshedin t In I'ionkkr\nwill 1m\u00bb run therequired length of line, and\nwhere the publication fee of *\u00bbi\\ ot t-n\npaidtheaffiidavitof proof of publirat <>n will\nbe sent to the officer before whom proof ismade\nWheie the fee has not been piwmiUv PHio\nwe shall hold affidavit until the biblical i<*n\nft-*-1\u00bb paid. This affidavit muM. be *ectied ie\nfore you can make proof, fin-b\u00bb*r,t way is >o\nremit the publication fee at l .*a?\u00bbt two w**eks\nbefore t!\u00bbe day .set for you to make vour t rool\n(Notice For Publication.\nDepartment of the Interior.\nU. S. Land Office at Gregory. >oibh Dakota\nDecember -4.\nNotice is hereby Riven that Kc* n! M.\nspouse,of Kunningviile. s D., wli n \u2022W M 'H\n10th. lUItJ, made Homestead Knt ra 1 i\u00ab \u00bbi\u2022\n>E M and NHS Ehi and >1 1* n\ngs, Township 43- N liang<*,c> N\\ o I*i*m\u00ab*i i\u00bbh 1\nMeridian, has Hied notice of intention to\nmake Three-Year proof, to estanli li elan*\ntu the land above desoribeu n\u00ab t r\u00ab i*\u2022 .i\nKirch, tJ, S, Commissioner at In* oltiee i,i\nWood.B. D..on the sth day of.l etu uar.\u00ab m:il.